# Tips

**Leverage automatic responsive behavior**: Table spacing tokens base on `--content-spacing`, so tables automatically scale for mobile, tablet, and print without explicit media queries. When you adjust document spacing, tables adapt proportionally. Print media automatically uses reduced spacing and transparent striping to save ink.

**Use appropriate striping**: Tables default to no striping (`transparent`) for a clean appearance. Enable row striping in your theme CSS file with `--table-row-striped: var(--color-gray-100)` for light mode and `--table-row-striped-dark: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.03)` (a subtle white overlay) for dark mode to improve readability in tables with many rows. The subtle alternating backgrounds help eyes track across wide tables. Note that striping examples don't work well with inline style overrides due to dark mode media query limitations.

**Customize hover feedback**: The `--table-row-hover` token provides interactive feedback when users scan tables. Match hover colors to your theme's accent color for brand consistency, or set to `transparent` to disable hover effects entirely.

**Header styling matters**: When tables include `<thead>` elements, use `--table-header-background` to distinguish headers from data. Define both light and dark variants (`--table-header-background-dark`) in your theme CSS file to ensure proper dark mode support. Note that simple markdown tables may not generate `<thead>` elements.

**Caption position**: Table captions appear above the table, providing context before users view the data. This differs from figure captions, which traditionally appear below. Adjust `--table-caption-spacing-bottom` to control the gap between caption and data.

**Maintain label consistency**: Table labels automatically inherit from semantic label tokens (`--label-font-weight`, `--label-font-style`), ensuring visual consistency with figure and equation labels throughout your document.

**Notes for citations**: Use table notes for data sources, methodological notes, or statistical annotations. The smaller font size and secondary text color create appropriate visual hierarchy without overwhelming the main data.

**Print optimization**: Tables automatically optimize for print with reduced cell padding (`--table-cell-padding-print`) and transparent striping (`--table-row-striped-print`). Override these tokens to customize print appearance for different document types.

**Dark mode integration**: Table headers, row hover, and row striping automatically adapt to dark themes through token variants. When customizing these tokens, always define both light and dark variants for optimal appearance in both modes.

**Test with real data**: Table styling looks different with actual data versus placeholder content. Test your customizations with representative datasets including edge cases like long cell content, empty cells, and varying row counts.

**Accessibility considerations**: Ensure sufficient contrast between header backgrounds and text, particularly when using custom colors. Row hover effects should be visible but not distracting. Test with keyboard navigation to verify hover states work with focus indicators.

**Granular border control**: Use edge-specific tokens (`--table-border-top-width`, `--table-border-bottom-width`, etc.) to achieve classic typographic patterns without custom CSS. For Tufte-style horizontal rules, set top and bottom widths to 1px and left/right to 0. For Booktabs formatting, use thicker top/bottom borders (2px) with a thin header separator (1px). The hierarchical token structure (base → edge-specific) lets you set defaults and override specific edges as needed.
